I just finished implementing a new user registration endpoint for our Express/TypeScript API. Here's what I built:

```typescript
// src/routes/auth.ts
import { Router } from 'express';
import bcrypt from 'bcrypt';
import { z } from 'zod';
import { db } from '../db';
import { generateToken } from '../auth/jwt';

const registerSchema = z.object({
  email: z.string().email(),
  password: z.string().min(8),
  name: z.string().min(1),
});

router.post('/register', async (req, res) => {
  const parsed = registerSchema.safeParse(req.body);
  if (!parsed.success) return res.status(400).json({ errors: parsed.error.issues });

  const { email, password, name } = parsed.data;
  const existing = await db.user.findUnique({ where: { email } });
  if (existing) return res.status(409).json({ error: 'Email already registered' });

  const hashedPassword = await bcrypt.hash(password, 10);
  const user = await db.user.create({
    data: { email, password: hashedPassword, name, role: 'user' },
  });

  const token = generateToken({ userId: user.id, role: user.role });
  res.status(201).json({ token, user: { id: user.id, email: user.email, name: user.name } });
});
```

All 12 unit tests pass. Coverage on this file is 91%. I'm not sure about the error handling — should I be catching database errors? Also wondering if the bcrypt salt rounds (10) are sufficient. Can you help me prepare a review request for this?
